The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Firms chart cash course
                                                                                                               Firms chart cash course
          OUR BUREAU                          Assocham president Sajjan Jindal (centre) with general secretary D.S. Rawat (right) and IIFCL chairman S.S. Kohli in New Delhi on Wednesday. (PTI)                                  
	New Delhi, April 22: Industry is showing the first signs of rising from an investment slumber.        
	JSW Steel and Shree Cement today announced investment plans of Rs 3,000 crore and Rs 2,000 crore, respectively, while India Infrastructure Finance Company Ltd said it would lend Rs 6,000 crore in the current fiscal against Rs 3,200 crore in the previous year.         
	In addition, GAIL (India) said it would invest Rs 8,000 crore in a pipeline from the east coast to central and north India. Gujarat State Petronet Ltd has proposed a gas pipeline from the east coast to Rajasthan.        
	An upswing in cement, steel and infrastructure could have a strong ripple effect on the rest of the economy.         
	Our business plan is to invest Rs 3,000 crore in the current financial year. The investment will be spread across our plant in Vijaynagar (Karnataka) and upcoming projects in Jharkhand and Bengal, Sajjan Jindal, vice-chairman and managing director of JSW Steel, said on the sidelines of a conference here.        
	He said half of the investment would be from own reserves and the rest would be debt.        
	The two upcoming projects in Bengal and Jharkhand of 10 million tonnes per annum each will involve an investment of Rs 70,000 crore. For now, the investments in the two states will be in mining infrastructure.        
	Calcuttas Shree Cement will invest Rs 1,200 crore in expansion and new plants.        
	After expansion, the companys cement capacity will rise to 11.5 million tonnes (mt) per annum from 9mt.        
	New plants of 1mt each are coming up in Rajasthan and Uttarakhand. The company is also setting up four captive power plants in Rajasthan, where it already has three cement facilities.        
	Of the total investment, Rs 600 crore will go to the power plants while the rest will be invested in cement (capacity) expansion and infrastructure development, H.M. Bangur, managing director of the company, said.        
	Core sector boost        
	India Infrastructure Finance today said it would disburse Rs 6,000 crore in the current fiscal and raise Rs 5,000 crore through taxable bonds for refinancing projects such as highways and ports.         
	Chairman and managing director S.S. Kohli said they had raised Rs 500 crore from taxable bonds and planned to raise a similar amount through another issue by the end of this month. The bonds are for 15 years and carry a coupon rate of 7.9 per cent.                                                                                                                                        
